Step 2. Decade-wise Dispersion Ratio Changes

Calculate decade-by-decade changes for each dispersion ratio by grouping the data into ten‐year intervals and computing the difference in each ratio between the first and last year of each decade.

pacman::p_load(dplyr)

df %>%
  arrange(Year) %>%
  mutate(decade = paste0(floor(Year/10) * 10, "s")) %>%
  group_by(decade) %>%
  summarise(
    diff_90_10  = last(`90th/10th`)  - first(`90th/10th`),
    diff_90_50  = last(`90th/50th`)  - first(`90th/50th`),
    diff_50_10  = last(`50th/10th`)  - first(`50th/10th`)
  )

pacman::p_load(dplyr)

df <- read_csv(
  "household_income_dispersion.csv",
  locale = locale(grouping_mark = ",")
) %>%
  filter(Year >= 1967 & Year <= 2023) %>%
  select(Year, `90th/10th`, `90th/50th`, `50th/10th`) %>%
  pivot_longer(-Year, names_to = "ratio", values_to = "value")

ggplot(df, aes(x = Year, y = value, color = ratio)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  labs(
    title = "Income Dispersion Ratios (1967–2023)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Dispersion Ratio",
    color = "Ratio"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14, hjust = 0.5),

Step 4. Changepoint Analysis of Income Inequality Ratios

Perform a statistical changepoint analysis on the 90th/10th ratio time series to identify and test the timing of key inflection points in income inequality trends.

pacman::p_load(readr)
pacman::p_load(dplyr)
pacman::p_load(changepoint)
df <- read_csv("household_income_dispersion.csv", locale = locale(grouping_mark = ",")) %>%
  filter(Year >= 1967 & Year <= 2023) %>%
  arrange(Year)
ts_90_10 <- ts(df$`90th/10th`, start = df$Year[1], frequency = 1)
cp_90_10 <- cpt.mean(ts_90_10, method = "PELT", penalty = "BIC")
changepoints <- cpts(cp_90_10)
summary(cp_90_10)

Step 5. Piecewise Regression of Inequality Growth Rate

Fit a piecewise linear regression on the 90th/10th ratio time series using the detected changepoints to estimate the rate of inequality growth within each segment.

pacman::p_load(readr)
pacman::p_load(dplyr)
pacman::p_load(changepoint)
pacman::p_load(segmented)

df <- read_csv("household_income_dispersion.csv", locale = locale(grouping_mark = ",")) %>%
  filter(Year >= 1967 & Year <= 2023) %>%
  arrange(Year)

ts_90_10 <- ts(df$`90th/10th`, start = df$Year[1], frequency = 1)
cp_90_10 <- cpt.mean(ts_90_10, method = "PELT", penalty = "BIC")
break_years <- df$Year[cpts(cp_90_10)]

lm_base <- lm(`90th/10th` ~ Year, data = df)
seg_fit <- segmented(lm_base, seg.Z = ~Year, psi = break_years)
summary(seg_fit)

agr_decade <- df %>%

AI-generated summary

We compiled and analyzed household‐income data from 1967 through 2023, focusing on both raw percentile incomes (10th, 30th, 50th, 70th, 90th, 95th) and three dispersion ratios (90/10, 90/50, 50/10). Our goal was to trace long‐run inequality trends, identify inflection points, and compare dispersion dynamics across income segments.

Main steps:

  1. Data ingestion and cleaning – loaded the CSV, parsed numeric fields, and filtered to years 1967–2023.
  2. Computed and plotted time series of the three dispersion ratios to visualize overall trajectories and acceleration in inequality.
  3. Grouped data by decade to calculate decade‐by‐decade changes in each ratio.
  4. Applied changepoint detection on the 90/10 ratio, finding significant mean‐shifts around the early 1980s, mid‐1990s, and 2000s.
  5. Fitted a piecewise linear regression on the 90/10 series using detected breakpoints to estimate the rate of inequality growth in each segment.
  6. Plotted raw income trajectories by percentile to show how incomes at the top have risen much faster than those at the bottom.
  7. Calculated and plotted annualized growth rates by decade for each percentile income series.

Key results and observations:
• All three dispersion ratios rose over the 56‐year span, with the 90/10 ratio showing the steepest and most sustained increase.
• Changepoint analysis pinpointed the early 1980s as a major inflection when inequality began accelerating, followed by further shifts in the 1990s and 2000s.
• Piecewise regressions confirmed a modest pre‐1980 slope in the 90/10 ratio, followed by steeper growth post‐1980 and again in recent decades.
• Income trajectories reveal that top percentiles (90th and 95th) have grown markedly faster—often doubling or tripling—in nominal terms than bottom percentiles (10th and 30th), whose growth has been much more subdued.
• Decade‐by‐decade annualized growth rates show that the 2000s and 2010s saw the highest gains at the top, while lower percentiles experienced single‐digit annual growth.

Conclusions:
Over the last five-plus decades U.S. household income inequality has risen sharply, driven primarily by outsized gains at the top of the distribution. The most pronounced acceleration began in the early 1980s and has persisted through the 2000s and 2010s. While median incomes have grown modestly, the gap between top and bottom earners has widened significantly, underscoring a long‐term intensification of income disparity.
